rsies and international concerns have moulded Ottawa’s response to developments such as Ireland’s neutrality in the Second World War, its unsettled relationship with the Commonwealth, and the always contentious issue of Irish unification. In Canada and Ireland, Philip J. Currie painstakingly investigates the origins, trials, and successes of the sometimes turbulent connection between the two countries to shed new light on an important relationship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486329240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774863292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774863292/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles